.SS rx
.PP
Usage:
\f[C]rx\ <start\ |\ stop\ |\ wait\ |\ config\ [param=val\ [param=val\ [...]]>\f[]
.PP
Receive IQ samples and write them to the specified file.
Reception is controlled and configured by one of the following:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]start\f[] \- Start receiving samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]stop\f[] \- Stop Receiving samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]wait\f[] \- Wait for sample transmission to complete, or until a
specified amount of time elapses
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]config\f[] \- Configure sample reception.
If no parameters are provided, the current parameters are printed.
.PP
Running \[aq]\f[C]rx\f[]\[aq] without any additional commands is valid
shorthand for \[aq]\f[C]rx\ config\f[]\[aq].
.PP
The \f[C]wait\f[] command takes an optional timeout parameter.
This parameter defaults to units of milliseconds (\f[C]ms\f[]).
The timeout unit may be specified using the \f[C]ms\f[], \f[C]s\f[],
\f[C]m\f[], or \f[C]h\f[] suffixes.
If this parameter is not provided, the command will wait until the
reception completes or \f[C]Ctrl\-C\f[] is pressed.
.PP
Configuration parameters take the form \[aq]\f[C]param=value\[aq]\f[],
and may be specified in a single or multiple
\[aq]\f[C]rx\ config\f[]\[aq] invocations.
Below is a list of available parameters.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]n\f[] \- Number of samples to receive.
0 = inf.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]file\f[] \- Filename to write received samples to
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]format\f[] \- Output file format.
One of the following:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]csv\f[] \- CSV of SC16 Q11 samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]bin\f[] \- Raw SC16 Q11 DAC samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]samples\f[] \- Number of samples per buffer to use in the
asynchronous stream.
Must be divisible by 1024 and >= 1024.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]buffers\f[] \- Number of sample buffers to use in the asynchronous
stream.
The min value is 4.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]xfers\f[] \- Number of simultaneous transfers to allow the
asynchronous stream to use.
This should be less than the \[aq]\f[C]buffers\f[]\[aq] parameter.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]timeout\f[] \- Data stream timeout.
With no suffix, the default unit is \f[C]ms\f[].
The default value is 1s.
Valid suffixes are \[aq]\f[C]ms\f[]\[aq] and \[aq]\f[C]s\f[]\[aq].
.PP
Example:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]rx\ config\ file=/tmp/data.bin\ format=bin\ n=10K\f[]
.RS 2
.PP
Receive (10240 = 10 * 1024) samples, writing them to
\f[C]/tmp/data.bin\f[] in the binary DAC format.
.RE
.PP
Notes:
.IP \[bu] 2
The \f[C]n\f[], \f[C]samples\f[], \f[C]buffers\f[], and \f[C]xfers\f[]
parameters support the suffixes \[aq]\f[C]K\f[]\[aq],
\[aq]\f[C]M\f[]\[aq], and \[aq]\f[C]G\f[]\[aq], which are multiples of
1024.
.IP \[bu] 2
An \[aq]\f[C]rx\ stop\f[]\[aq] followed by an
\[aq]\f[C]rx\ start\f[]\[aq] will result in the samples file being
truncated.
If this is not desired, be sure to run \[aq]\f[C]rx\ config\f[]\[aq] to
set another file before restarting the rx stream.
.IP \[bu] 2
For higher sample rates, it is advised that the binary output format be
used, and the output file be written to RAM (e.g.
\f[C]/tmp\f[], \f[C]/dev/shm\f[]), if space allows.
For larger captures at higher sample rates, consider using an SSD
instead of a HDD.
.SS tx
.PP
Usage: \f[C]tx\ <start\ |\ stop\ |\ wait\ |\ config\ [parameters]>\f[]
.PP
Read IQ samples from the specified file and transmit them.
Transmission is controlled and configured by one of the following:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]start\f[] \- Start transmitting samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]stop\f[] \- Stop transmitting samples
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]wait\f[] \- Wait for sample transmission to complete, or until a
specified amount of time elapses
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]config\f[] \- Configure sample transmission .
If no parameters are provided, the current parameters are printed.
.PP
Running \[aq]\f[C]tx\f[]\[aq] without any additional commands is valid
shorthand for \[aq]\f[C]tx\ config\f[]\[aq].
.PP
The wait command takes an optional timeout parameter.
This parameter defaults to units of milliseconds (\f[C]ms\f[]).
The timeout unit may be specified using the \f[C]ms\f[], \f[C]s\f[],
\f[C]m\f[], or \f[C]h\f[] suffixes.
If this parameter is not provided, the command will wait until the
transmission completes or \f[C]Ctrl\-C\f[] is pressed.
.PP
Configuration parameters take the form \[aq]\f[C]param=value\f[]\[aq],
and may be specified in a single or multiple
\[aq]\f[C]tx\ config\f[]\[aq] invocations.
Below is a list of available parameters.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]file\f[] \- Filename to read samples from
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]format\f[] \- Output file format.
One of the following:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]csv\f[] \- CSV of SC16 Q11 samples ([\-2048, 2047])
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]bin\f[] \- Raw SC16 Q11 DAC samples ([\-2048, 2047])
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]repeat\f[] \- The number of times the file contents should be
transmitted.
0 implies repeat until stopped.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]delay\f[] \- The number of microseconds to delay between
retransmitting file contents.
0 implies no delay.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]samples\f[] \- Number of samples per buffer to use in the
asynchronous stream.
Must be divisible by 1024 and >= 1024.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]buffers\f[] \- Number of sample buffers to use in the asynchronous
stream.
The min value is 4.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]xfers\f[] \- Number of simultaneous transfers to allow the
asynchronous stream to use.
This should be < the \[aq]buffers\[aq] parameter.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]timeout\f[] \- Data stream timeout.
With no suffix, the default unit is ms.
The default value is 1s.
Valid suffixes are \[aq]ms\[aq] and \[aq]s\[aq].
.PP
Example:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]tx\ config\ file=data.bin\ format=bin\ repeat=2\ delay=250000\f[]
.RS 2
.PP
Transmitting the contents of \f[C]data.bin\f[] two times, with a ~250ms
delay between transmissions.
.RE
.PP
Notes:
.IP \[bu] 2
The \f[C]n\f[], \f[C]samples\f[], \f[C]buffers\f[], and \f[C]xfers\f[]
parameters support the suffixes \[aq]\f[C]K\f[]\[aq],
\[aq]\f[C]M\f[]\[aq], and \[aq]\f[C]G\f[]\[aq], which are multiples of
1024.
.IP \[bu] 2
For higher sample rates, it is advised that the input file be stored in
RAM (e.g.
\f[C]/tmp\f[], \f[C]/dev/shm\f[]) or to an SSD, rather than a HDD.
.IP \[bu] 2
When providing CSV data, this command will first convert it to a binary
format, stored in a file in the current working directory.
During this process, out\-of\-range values will be clamped.
.IP \[bu] 2
When using a binary format, the user is responsible for ensuring that
the provided data values are within the allowed range.
This prerequisite alleviates the need for this program to perform range
checks in time\-sensitive callbacks.
.SS set
.PP
Usage: \f[C]set\ <param>\ <arguments>\f[]
.PP
The set command takes a parameter and an arbitrary number of arguments
for that particular command.
The parameter is one of:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]bandwidth\f[] \- Bandwidth settings
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]frequency\f[] \- Frequency settings
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]gpio\f[] \- FX3 <\-> FPGA GPIO state
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]loopback\f[] \- Loopback settings
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]lnagain\f[] \- Gain setting of the LNA, in dB.
Valid values are 0, 3, 6.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]rxvga1\f[] \- Gain setting of RXVGA1, in dB.
Range: [5, 30]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]rxvga2\f[] \- Gain setting of RXVGA2, in dB.
Range: [0, 30]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]txvga1\f[] \- Gain setting of TXVGA1, in dB.
Range: [\-35, \-4]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]txvga2\f[] \- Gain setting of TXVGA2, in dB.
Range: [0, 25]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]sampling\f[] \- External or internal sampling mode
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]samplerate\f[] \- Samplerate settings
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]trimdac\f[] \- VCTCXO Trim DAC settings
.SS version
.PP
Usage: \f[C]version\f[]
.PP
Prints version information for host software and the current device
